## .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration

### Breaking Changes & Bugs in the Original

| Issue | Severity |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort()`** — throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+ | 🔴 Won't compile |
| **`Thread.Interrupt()`** — works but fragile; not recommended | 🟡 Deprecated pattern |
| **Race condition** — two rapid `Enqueue` calls → `ManualResetEvent` coalesces signals → second item stranded until next enqueue | 🔴 Bug (data loss) |
| **Empty-queue crash** — if signaled with empty queue, `Dequeue()` throws `InvalidOperationException` | 🔴 Bug |
| No graceful shutdown / cancellation | 🟡 Design gap |

---

### Migrated Code (idiomatic .NET 8)

Replace the entire class with `Channel<T>`, which is the modern bounded/unbounded producer-consumer primitive that fixes every issue above:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _worker;

    public void Start()
    {
        _worker = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        // ReadAllAsync yields items as they arrive — no manual
        // signaling, no lock, no race condition.
        await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
        {
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        // TryWrite on an unbounded channel always succeeds
        // unless the writer has been completed.
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Processor has been stopped.");
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        // 1. Signal the writer is done — ReadAllAsync will drain and exit.
        _channel.Writer.TryComplete();

        // 2. Give the worker time to finish draining.
        if (_worker is not null)
        {
            using var timeout = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
            try
            {
                await _worker.WaitAsync(timeout.Token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException)
            {
                // Drain timed out — force cancel.
                await _cts.CancelAsync();
            }
        }

        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // your processing logic
    }
}
```

### Why This Is Better

| Old pattern | New pattern | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` + `lock` + `Queue` | `Channel<T>` | Thread-safe, backpressure-aware, zero manual signaling |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` + `Writer.Complete()` | Graceful shutdown, no `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| Raw `Thread` | `Task.Run` | Uses ThreadPool, integrates with `async`/`await` |
| Signal coalescing bug | `ReadAllAsync` drains all available items | No lost messages |

### Key Pitfalls to Watch

1. **`Thread.Abort` → just delete it.** There is no 1:1 replacement. Use cooperative cancellation (`CancellationToken`) instead.
2. **`Thread.Interrupt`** still exists in .NET 8 but only wakes `Thread.Sleep`/`Join` — it does **not** wake `WaitOne` reliably on all platforms.
3. If `Handle()` is async, change the signature to `async Task` and `await` it directly — no `.Result` or `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()`.
4. For **bounded** channels (backpressure), swap `CreateUnbounded` → `CreateBounded<string>(capacity)` and switch to `await _channel.Writer.WriteAsync(item)`.
